Quote:  <i>Ma&#769;.pa-u</i> (ma.&#769;.pa.-u; <i>colloq.</i> m&adot.&#769;.pou), <i> n</i>. [Maori] <i>Ma&#769;.po-u</i>(ma.&#769;.p&omacr.-u;<i> colloq</i>. m&adot.&#769;.pu), <i> (Bot.)</i> A New Zealand tree<i> Myrsine Urvillei</i>), of the order <i>Myrsineae</i>; called also <i>matapou, matapo, matipo,</i> and <i>maple. [Local, N. Z.] Black mapau, </i>name applied incorrectly by New Zealand settlers to the tree <i>Pittosporum tenuifolium</i>, of the order <i>Pittosporeae. - White mapau, (a) </i>The tarata <i>(Pittosporum eugenoides);</i> -called also <i>turpentine tree. (b) </i>The saxifragaceous tree piripiri <i>(Carpodetus serratus); called often mapou.</i> See PIRIPIRI.
